The Chesapeake Bay Foundation is taking legal action against the EPA over nitrogen pollution, crucial for algae growth.
Oysters, once abundant, are now scarce due to over-harvesting and disease.
Watermen have agreed to halt harvesting in managed reserves to allow oysters to grow.
Maryland watermen are also considering a lawsuit against polluters.
Nutria eradication efforts have seen success in Maryland.
The menhaden industry is under scrutiny for overfishing, impacting the bay ecosystem.
Asian oysters are being considered as a potential solution, but concerns about their impact on native species persist.
